Note:
Python Semantic Analyzer - Type checking, scope analysis, and semantic validation for Python AST
Handles Python's dynamic typing, duck typing, metaclasses, decorators, and module system.
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/python/python_parser.runa" as Parser
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as Dict

@Reasoning:
Ten-slot semantic state object. global_scope is the module-level symbol
table; current_scope mutates as the analyzer descends into nested
function/class bodies; scope_stack supports save/restore on enter/exit
of nested scopes. The five registries (module/class/function/import/
decorator) index named declarations by string -> info-record so
cross-reference resolution is O(1). error_message and has_error
collect a single fatal-error signal for internal failures.
@End Reasoning
Type called "PythonSemanticAnalyzer":
    global_scope as Integer
    current_scope as Integer
    scope_stack as Integer
    module_registry as Integer
    class_registry as Integer
    function_registry as Integer
    import_registry as Integer
    decorator_registry as Integer
    error_message as Integer
    has_error as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Construction allocates an 80-byte struct (ten 8-byte slots) directly via Layout.allocate to keep field offsets stable across versions. global_scope is reused for both slot 0 (global) and slot 8 (initial current_scope) so the analyzer starts in module scope; the seven container slots are populated with empty Dict/List instances so consumers never need to null-check before set/get.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Field layout: 0=global_scope, 8=current_scope, 16=scope_stack, 24=module_registry, 32=class_registry, 40=function_registry, 48=import_registry, 56=decorator_registry, 64=error_message, 72=has_error. Layout offsets are checked against every accessor in this file; a struct field move requires updating all memory_get_int64/memory_set_int64 call sites.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_python_semantic_analyzer" returns Integer:
    Note: Create Python semantic analyzer with dynamic typing support

    Let analyzer_size be 80
    Let analyzer be proc allocate from Layout with analyzer_size

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let global_scope be proc create from Dict
    Let scope_stack be proc create from List
    Let module_registry be proc create from Dict
    Let class_registry be proc create from Dict
    Let function_registry be proc create from Dict
    Let import_registry be proc create from Dict
    Let decorator_registry be proc create from Dict

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0, global_scope
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8, global_scope
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 16, scope_stack
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 24, module_registry
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 32, class_registry
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 40, function_registry
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 48, import_registry
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 56, decorator_registry
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 64, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 72, 0

    Return analyzer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Analysis is structured as five sequential phases (imports, declarations, decorators, classes, functions) because each later phase consumes data the prior phase populated; merging them would force every phase to either re-walk the AST or carry partial-state assumptions. The has_error check at the end short-circuits return-1 when any phase signaled a fatal condition via set_python_semantic_error.
@End Reasoning
@Security_Scope:
program_node comes from untrusted user source; the null check guards against a parser returning 0 on malformed input, and set_python_semantic_error stores a heap-copy of the error message so a transient string in the caller cannot dangle.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "analyze_python_program" takes analyzer as Integer, program_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Perform complete semantic analysis on Python program

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If program_node is equal to 0:
        proc set_python_semantic_error with analyzer, "Null program node"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Phase 1: Collect all imports and module references
    proc collect_python_imports with analyzer, program_node

    Note: Phase 2: Collect all class and function declarations
    proc collect_python_declarations with analyzer, program_node

    Note: Phase 3: Validate decorators and metaclasses
    proc validate_python_decorators from analyzer

    Note: Phase 4: Analyze class hierarchies and method resolution
    proc analyze_python_classes from analyzer

    Note: Phase 5: Analyze function bodies and expressions
    proc analyze_python_functions with analyzer, program_node

    Let has_error be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 72
    If has_error is equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Imports are collected in a dedicated pass before any declaration analysis so module references at the top of a Python file can be resolved when declarations later reference imported names. PYTHON_IMPORT and PYTHON_FROM_IMPORT are dispatched to separate collectors because their target shapes (module list vs name list) differ.
@End Reasoning
Process called "collect_python_imports" takes analyzer as Integer, program_node as Integer:
    Note: Collect all import statements for module resolution

    If program_node is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let import_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 48

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with program_node, 32
    If children is not equal to 0:
        Let child_count be proc size from List with children
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than child_count:
            Let child be proc get from List with children, i
            Let child_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with child, 0

            If child_type is equal to PYTHON_IMPORT from Parser:
                proc collect_import_statement with analyzer, child
            Otherwise If child_type is equal to PYTHON_FROM_IMPORT from Parser:
                proc collect_from_import_statement with analyzer, child
            End If

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Records one "import module [as alias]" statement in the import_registry
keyed by the module name. The alias (if any) is stored as a secondary
field on the entry so name resolution can rewrite references back to
the canonical module name.
@End Reasoning
Process called "collect_import_statement" takes analyzer as Integer, import_node as Integer:
    Note: Collect import statement information

    Let import_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 48
    Let module_name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with import_node, 8
    Let import_alias be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with import_node, 16

    If module_name is not equal to 0:
        Let import_info be proc create from Dict
        proc set from Dict with import_info, "type", "import"
        proc set from Dict with import_info, "module", module_name

        If import_alias is not equal to 0:
            proc set from Dict with import_info, "alias", import_alias
        End If

        proc set from Dict with import_registry, module_name, import_info
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Records "from module import name1, name2, ..." statements. The list of
imported names (or the "*" sentinel for star-imports) is stored on the
entry so the validator can verify each name actually exists in the
source module during semantic analysis.
@End Reasoning
Process called "collect_from_import_statement" takes analyzer as Integer, from_import_node as Integer:
    Note: Collect from-import statement information

    Let import_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 48
    Let module_name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with from_import_node, 8
    Let imported_names be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with from_import_node, 16

    If module_name is not equal to 0:
        Let import_info be proc create from Dict
        proc set from Dict with import_info, "type", "from_import"
        proc set from Dict with import_info, "module", module_name

        If imported_names is not equal to 0:
            proc set from Dict with import_info, "names", imported_names
        End If

        proc set from Dict with import_registry, module_name, import_info
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
A separate declaration-collection pass runs before validation so forward references work (Python allows referring to a class defined later in the same module). PYTHON_CLASS, PYTHON_FUNCTION, and PYTHON_ASYNC_FUNCTION each dispatch to a specialized collector because their registry shapes differ (classes carry bases/metaclass, functions don't).
@End Reasoning
Process called "collect_python_declarations" takes analyzer as Integer, program_node as Integer:
    Note: Collect all class and function declarations

    If program_node is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let class_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 32
    Let function_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 40

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with program_node, 32
    If children is not equal to 0:
        Let child_count be proc size from List with children
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than child_count:
            Let child be proc get from List with children, i
            Let child_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with child, 0

            If child_type is equal to PYTHON_CLASS from Parser:
                proc collect_class_declaration with analyzer, child
            Otherwise If child_type is equal to PYTHON_FUNCTION from Parser:
                proc collect_function_declaration with analyzer, child
            Otherwise If child_type is equal to PYTHON_ASYNC_FUNCTION from Parser:
                proc collect_async_function_declaration with analyzer, child
            End If

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Registers a class in the class_registry along with its inheritance
information: base-class list (for MRO computation), optional metaclass
(for Python 3 metaclass dispatch), and decorator list (for decorator-
order validation). All four fields are read directly from documented
AST node offsets — see python_parser for the layout.
@End Reasoning
Process called "collect_class_declaration" takes analyzer as Integer, class_node as Integer:
    Note: Collect class declaration with inheritance and metaclass info

    Let class_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 32
    Let class_name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with class_node, 8

    If class_name is not equal to 0:
        Let class_info be proc create from Dict
        proc set from Dict with class_info, "node", class_node

        Note: Collect base classes
        Let bases be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with class_node, 16
        If bases is not equal to 0:
            proc set from Dict with class_info, "bases", bases
        End If

        Note: Collect metaclass if specified
        Let metaclass be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with class_node, 24
        If metaclass is not equal to 0:
            proc set from Dict with class_info, "metaclass", metaclass
        End If

        Note: Collect decorators
        Let decorators be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with class_node, 32
        If decorators is not equal to 0:
            proc set from Dict with class_info, "decorators", decorators
        End If

        proc set from Dict with class_registry, class_name, class_info
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Registers a function in function_registry along with its parameters and
decorators. The type field is set to "function" (vs "async_function")
to let later passes branch on synchronous vs asynchronous semantics
without re-inspecting the AST node.
@End Reasoning
Process called "collect_function_declaration" takes analyzer as Integer, func_node as Integer:
    Note: Collect function declaration with signature and decorator info

    Let function_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 40
    Let func_name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with func_node, 8

    If func_name is not equal to 0:
        Let func_info be proc create from Dict
        proc set from Dict with func_info, "node", func_node
        proc set from Dict with func_info, "type", "function"

        Note: Collect parameters
        Let params be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with func_node, 16
        If params is not equal to 0:
            proc set from Dict with func_info, "parameters", params
        End If

        Note: Collect decorators
        Let decorators be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with func_node, 32
        If decorators is not equal to 0:
            proc set from Dict with func_info, "decorators", decorators
        End If

        proc set from Dict with function_registry, func_name, func_info
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Same as collect_function_declaration but with type="async_function". The
separate entry lets the validator enforce async-only rules — await/
async with/async for can only appear inside an async function, and
async functions cannot be invoked synchronously.
@End Reasoning
Process called "collect_async_function_declaration" takes analyzer as Integer, async_func_node as Integer:
    Note: Collect async function declaration

    Let function_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 40
    Let func_name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with async_func_node, 8

    If func_name is not equal to 0:
        Let func_info be proc create from Dict
        proc set from Dict with func_info, "node", async_func_node
        proc set from Dict with func_info, "type", "async_function"

        Note: Collect parameters
        Let params be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with async_func_node, 16
        If params is not equal to 0:
            proc set from Dict with func_info, "parameters", params
        End If

        Note: Collect decorators
        Let decorators be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with async_func_node, 32
        If decorators is not equal to 0:
            proc set from Dict with func_info, "decorators", decorators
        End If

        proc set from Dict with function_registry, func_name, func_info
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Decorator validation runs after declarations are registered so both the decorator and its target are in scope. Splitting the work into validate_class_decorators and validate_function_decorators lets per-target rules (e.g., @dataclass requires a class, @staticmethod requires a function) be enforced in their own contexts.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_python_decorators" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Validate all decorators used in the program

    Let decorator_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 56
    Let class_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 32
    Let function_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 40

    Note: Validate class decorators
    proc validate_class_decorators with analyzer, class_registry

    Note: Validate function decorators
    proc validate_function_decorators with analyzer, function_registry
End Process

@Reasoning:
Iterates every registered class and runs its decorator list through
validate_decorator_list with target_type="class". Class-target
decorators have a restricted set (e.g. @dataclass, @final) versus
function-target decorators (e.g. @staticmethod, @classmethod) and the
target_type string drives that distinction in validate_individual_decorator.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_class_decorators" takes analyzer as Integer, class_registry as Integer:
    Note: Validate decorators applied to classes

    Let class_keys be proc keys from Dict with class_registry
    If class_keys is not equal to 0:
        Let key_count be proc size from List with class_keys
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than key_count:
            Let class_name be proc get from List with class_keys, i
            Let class_info be proc get from Dict with class_registry, class_name
            Let decorators be proc get from Dict with class_info, "decorators"

            If decorators is not equal to 0:
                proc validate_decorator_list with analyzer, decorators, "class"
            End If

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Symmetric to validate_class_decorators but with target_type="function".
Covers both sync and async functions since they share the same
function_registry. Each function's decorator list is iterated and
dispatched through validate_decorator_list.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_function_decorators" takes analyzer as Integer, function_registry as Integer:
    Note: Validate decorators applied to functions

    Let func_keys be proc keys from Dict with function_registry
    If func_keys is not equal to 0:
        Let key_count be proc size from List with func_keys
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than key_count:
            Let func_name be proc get from List with func_keys, i
            Let func_info be proc get from Dict with function_registry, func_name
            Let decorators be proc get from Dict with func_info, "decorators"

            If decorators is not equal to 0:
                proc validate_decorator_list with analyzer, decorators, "function"
            End If

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Iterates each decorator in the supplied decorators list AST and routes
to validate_individual_decorator with the target_type ("class" /
"function") so per-decorator legality can be checked against its
intended target.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_decorator_list" takes analyzer as Integer, decorators as Integer, target_type as Integer:
    Note: Validate list of decorators for specific target type

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with decorators, 32
    If children is not equal to 0:
        Let child_count be proc size from List with children
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than child_count:
            Let decorator be proc get from List with children, i
            proc validate_individual_decorator with analyzer, decorator, target_type
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Dispatches a single decorator to either validate_builtin_decorator (for
known Python built-in decorators like @property/@staticmethod) or
validate_custom_decorator (for user-defined decorators which must
resolve through the function_registry). The is_builtin check is the
fast path; custom decorator validation involves a registry lookup.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_individual_decorator" takes analyzer as Integer, decorator as Integer, target_type as Integer:
    Note: Validate individual decorator

    Let decorator_name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with decorator, 8
    If decorator_name is not equal to 0:
        Let is_builtin be proc is_builtin_decorator with analyzer, decorator_name
        If is_builtin is equal to 1:
            proc validate_builtin_decorator with analyzer, decorator_name, target_type
        Otherwise:
            proc validate_custom_decorator with analyzer, decorator_name, target_type
        End If
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Linear-scan check against the canonical Python built-in decorator
names: property, staticmethod, classmethod, dataclass, abstractmethod,
cached_property, lru_cache, wraps, overload, final. Returns 1 on
match, 0 otherwise. The list is constructed inline because the set is
small and call frequency is low (only at validation time, not on a
hot path).
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_builtin_decorator" takes analyzer as Integer, decorator_name as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if decorator is a Python built-in decorator

    Let builtin_decorators be proc create from List
    proc list_append with builtin_decorators, "property"
    proc list_append with builtin_decorators, "staticmethod"
    proc list_append with builtin_decorators, "classmethod"
    proc list_append with builtin_decorators, "dataclass"
    proc list_append with builtin_decorators, "abstractmethod"
    proc list_append with builtin_decorators, "cached_property"
    proc list_append with builtin_decorators, "lru_cache"
    proc list_append with builtin_decorators, "wraps"
    proc list_append with builtin_decorators, "overload"
    proc list_append with builtin_decorators, "final"

    Let builtin_count be proc size from List with builtin_decorators
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than builtin_count:
        Let builtin_name be proc get from List with builtin_decorators, i
        Let matches be proc equals from StringCore with decorator_name, builtin_name
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Class-hierarchy analysis runs once over the class_registry instead of inline per-class because MRO computation requires the full set of classes to be registered first (a base class may itself be a later-declared class). Iterating keys keeps the analysis order-independent.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_python_classes" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Analyze class hierarchies and method resolution order

    Let class_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 32

    Let class_keys be proc keys from Dict with class_registry
    If class_keys is not equal to 0:
        Let key_count be proc size from List with class_keys
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than key_count:
            Let class_name be proc get from List with class_keys, i
            Let class_info be proc get from Dict with class_registry, class_name
            proc analyze_individual_class with analyzer, class_name, class_info
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Per-class analysis pipeline: MRO check (linearizes the base-class
DAG and detects cycles), special-method validation (verifies __init__/
__new__/__del__/__call__ signatures), and metaclass-usage validation
(checks compatibility between declared metaclass and inherited
metaclass).
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_individual_class" takes analyzer as Integer, class_name as Integer, class_info as Integer:
    Note: Analyze individual class definition

    Note: Check method resolution order
    proc check_method_resolution_order with analyzer, class_name, class_info

    Note: Validate special methods
    proc validate_special_methods with analyzer, class_name, class_info

    Note: Check metaclass consistency
    proc validate_metaclass_usage with analyzer, class_name, class_info
End Process

@Reasoning:
Function bodies are analyzed last (after imports, declarations, decorators, classes) so name resolution inside a function body can find all module-level symbols. Async functions and class methods take separate dispatches because their scope semantics differ (await is only legal in async, class methods see self/cls).
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_python_functions" takes analyzer as Integer, program_node as Integer:
    Note: Analyze function bodies and method implementations

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with program_node, 32
    If children is not equal to 0:
        Let child_count be proc size from List with children
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than child_count:
            Let child be proc get from List with children, i
            Let child_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with child, 0

            If child_type is equal to PYTHON_FUNCTION from Parser:
                proc analyze_function_body with analyzer, child
            Otherwise If child_type is equal to PYTHON_ASYNC_FUNCTION from Parser:
                proc analyze_async_function_body with analyzer, child
            Otherwise If child_type is equal to PYTHON_CLASS from Parser:
                proc analyze_class_methods with analyzer, child
            End If

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Per-function analysis: enters a new function-local scope, processes
parameter declarations (which become locals in the new scope), recurses
into the body via analyze_statement_block, then pops back to the
enclosing scope. The enter/exit pairing must be symmetric to keep
scope_stack consistent.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_function_body" takes analyzer as Integer, func_node as Integer:
    Note: Analyze function body for semantic correctness

    proc enter_function_scope from analyzer

    Note: Analyze function parameters
    proc analyze_function_parameters with analyzer, func_node

    Note: Analyze function body statements
    Let body be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with func_node, 24
    If body is not equal to 0:
        proc analyze_statement_block with analyzer, body
    End If

    proc exit_function_scope from analyzer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Walks every statement in a block sequentially and dispatches each
through analyze_statement. No new scope is pushed here — blocks in
Python do not introduce scoping (with the exception of comprehension
expressions and class bodies, which are handled separately).
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_statement_block" takes analyzer as Integer, block_node as Integer:
    Note: Analyze block of statements

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block_node, 32
    If children is not equal to 0:
        Let child_count be proc size from List with children
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than child_count:
            Let stmt be proc get from List with children, i
            proc analyze_statement with analyzer, stmt
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Polymorphic statement dispatch. Routes each PYTHON_* statement type to
its specialized analyzer: assignment/if/while/for/try/with/return/
yield/await/global/nonlocal/expression-statement. Unknown types are
silently dropped — the parser is responsible for emitting only valid
statement nodes, so an unknown type here would indicate a parser bug,
not a recoverable analyzer condition.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_statement" takes analyzer as Integer, stmt_node as Integer:
    Note: Analyze individual Python statements

    If stmt_node is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let stmt_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with stmt_node, 0

    If stmt_type is equal to PYTHON_ASSIGNMENT from Parser:
        proc analyze_assignment_statement with analyzer, stmt_node
    Otherwise If stmt_type is equal to PYTHON_IF from Parser:
        proc analyze_if_statement with analyzer, stmt_node
    Otherwise If stmt_type is equal to PYTHON_WHILE from Parser:
        proc analyze_while_statement with analyzer, stmt_node
    Otherwise If stmt_type is equal to PYTHON_FOR from Parser:
        proc analyze_for_statement with analyzer, stmt_node
    Otherwise If stmt_type is equal to PYTHON_TRY from Parser:
        proc analyze_try_statement with analyzer, stmt_node
    Otherwise If stmt_type is equal to PYTHON_WITH from Parser:
        proc analyze_with_statement with analyzer, stmt_node
    Otherwise If stmt_type is equal to PYTHON_RETURN from Parser:
        proc analyze_return_statement with analyzer, stmt_node
    Otherwise If stmt_type is equal to PYTHON_YIELD from Parser:
        proc analyze_yield_statement with analyzer, stmt_node
    Otherwise If stmt_type is equal to PYTHON_AWAIT from Parser:
        proc analyze_await_statement with analyzer, stmt_node
    Otherwise If stmt_type is equal to PYTHON_GLOBAL from Parser:
        proc analyze_global_statement with analyzer, stmt_node
    Otherwise If stmt_type is equal to PYTHON_NONLOCAL from Parser:
        proc analyze_nonlocal_statement with analyzer, stmt_node
    Otherwise If stmt_type is equal to PYTHON_EXPRESSION_STMT from Parser:
        proc analyze_expression_statement with analyzer, stmt_node
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Pushes a new empty scope dict onto scope_stack and points current_scope
to it. Bindings introduced by parameter declarations and local
assignments will land in this dict; lookups falling through can walk
back through scope_stack to find enclosing scopes (lexical closure).
@End Reasoning
Process called "enter_function_scope" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Enter new scope for function analysis

    Let scope_stack be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 16
    Let new_scope be proc create from Dict
    proc list_append with scope_stack, new_scope

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8, new_scope
End Process

@Reasoning:
Pops the most recently pushed scope dict from scope_stack and updates
current_scope to point at the next-deepest scope (or global_scope if
the stack is now empty). The popped scope dict is discarded — the
analysis pipeline does not retain function-local symbol tables after
the function body has been visited.
@End Reasoning
Process called "exit_function_scope" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Exit current function scope

    Let scope_stack be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 16
    Let stack_size be proc size from List with scope_stack

    If stack_size is greater than 0:
        Let popped_scope be proc list_pop from List with scope_stack
        Let new_size be stack_size minus 1

        If new_size is greater than 0:
            Let current_scope be proc get from List with scope_stack, new_size minus 1
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8, current_scope
        Otherwise:
            Let global_scope be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8, global_scope
        End If
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Records a variable binding in the current scope dict. The var_info
record carries type/initialization information needed by downstream
analyses (type inference, dead-code detection). No shadowing check is
performed here — Python explicitly allows rebinding of names within
the same scope.
@End Reasoning
Process called "register_variable_in_scope" takes analyzer as Integer, var_name as Integer, var_info as Integer:
    Note: Register variable in current scope

    Let current_scope be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8
    If current_scope is not equal to 0:
        proc set from Dict with current_scope, var_name, var_info
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Linear-scan check against the canonical Python built-in function names
(len/str/int/float/bool/list/dict/tuple/set/range/enumerate/zip/map/
filter/sorted/reversed/any/all/sum/min/max/abs/round/print/input/open/
type/isinstance/issubclass/getattr/setattr/hasattr/delattr/callable).
Returns 1 on match so undefined-name checks can avoid flagging
builtins as undefined.
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_builtin_function" takes analyzer as Integer, func_name as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if function is a Python built-in

    Let builtin_functions be proc create from List
    proc list_append with builtin_functions, "len"
    proc list_append with builtin_functions, "str"
    proc list_append with builtin_functions, "int"
    proc list_append with builtin_functions, "float"
    proc list_append with builtin_functions, "bool"
    proc list_append with builtin_functions, "list"
    proc list_append with builtin_functions, "dict"
    proc list_append with builtin_functions, "tuple"
    proc list_append with builtin_functions, "set"
    proc list_append with builtin_functions, "range"
    proc list_append with builtin_functions, "enumerate"
    proc list_append with builtin_functions, "zip"
    proc list_append with builtin_functions, "map"
    proc list_append with builtin_functions, "filter"
    proc list_append with builtin_functions, "sorted"
    proc list_append with builtin_functions, "reversed"
    proc list_append with builtin_functions, "any"
    proc list_append with builtin_functions, "all"
    proc list_append with builtin_functions, "sum"
    proc list_append with builtin_functions, "min"
    proc list_append with builtin_functions, "max"
    proc list_append with builtin_functions, "abs"
    proc list_append with builtin_functions, "round"
    proc list_append with builtin_functions, "print"
    proc list_append with builtin_functions, "input"
    proc list_append with builtin_functions, "open"
    proc list_append with builtin_functions, "type"
    proc list_append with builtin_functions, "isinstance"
    proc list_append with builtin_functions, "issubclass"
    proc list_append with builtin_functions, "getattr"
    proc list_append with builtin_functions, "setattr"
    proc list_append with builtin_functions, "hasattr"
    proc list_append with builtin_functions, "delattr"
    proc list_append with builtin_functions, "callable"

    Let builtin_count be proc size from List with builtin_functions
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than builtin_count:
        Let builtin_name be proc get from List with builtin_functions, i
        Let matches be proc equals from StringCore with func_name, builtin_name
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Records a fatal semantic error: sets has_error=1 then copies the
message into a heap-owned buffer stored in the error_message slot.
The deep copy is required because the caller may pass a transient
string that would be freed before the error is consumed.
@End Reasoning
Process called "set_python_semantic_error" takes analyzer as Integer, message as Integer:
    Note: Set semantic analyzer error state

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 72, 1

    Let error_copy be proc copy_string from StringCore with message
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 64, error_copy
End Process